    About this Competition

    You are provided with an anonymized dataset containing numeric feature variables, the numeric target column, and a string ID column.

    The task is to predict the value of target column in the test set.

    File descriptions

    • test.csv - the test set
    • sample_submission.csv - a sample submission file in the correct format

    Anton Loss•Posted on Version 5•6 months ago•Options•Reply
    3

    Well, may I state the obvious?

    Looks like data is time-separated. This is the most common way data is split for Kaggle challenges, and given nature of Santander, it's extremely likely that we're working with two distinct time periods.

    Dropping some rows/columns from the test set could be of the more obvious way of dealing with this. Though there are probably more sophisticated ways.

    What is more important to know, is that - is the target "scaled"? Do we need to "extrapolate"?

    Assume that mean of the "target" in the test is larger than in the train. In this case, Gradient Boosting might not be the best solution (since it can't extrapolate), and we would need some kind of a linear model or Neural Nets.

    The only way to test this is to either split train itself into time-periods. Or, probe the leaderboard.

    Both options seem very hard!

    Thanks for a great notebook! :)

    Yukihiro•Posted on Version 8•6 months ago•Options•Reply

    I am a beginner in terms of statistics. It is a question about outliers. I know normalization, but why do a log-transform prior to scaling?

    SUDHIR KUMAR SHAHU•Posted on Version 8•6 months ago•Options•Reply
    3

    In simple terms, we take log-transform when few values in data set are being quite small as compared to outliners, so the relationship looks like exponential relationship. To bring it into linear relationship we take log of values(same as we do in case of pH in Chemistry).

    A = B^p (Exponential relationship between A and B)

    Taking log

    log(A) = p*log(B) (Linear relationship between log(A) and log(B))

    Also if we will not take log before scaling, then after scaling the smaller values will become quite small in fractions and outliers will take value near to 1.

    I'm thinking there are several ways to think about this, but overall if there's a row in the test set completely unrelated to the training set, then it's going to be hard to predict no matter what. However, knowing that there are differences in the distributions could be relevant in terms of feature engineering, in that certain features which distinguish users in the test set, but are completely unrelated to those in training, should not be used for further engineering, and vice versa for features equally distributed among training/testing.

    I'd be very interested to hear what other have to say on this subject though

    Henrique Mello•Posted on Latest Version•5 months ago•Options•Reply
    0

    "Test set" is somewhat a misleading name. Here, the test set has only the predictor variables so we can predict the target (therefore we don't know what that value is). Kaggle has the "true target value" for the test set and uses it to compare to what you predicted and generate your score for the competition.

    In order to test your model locally, a good approach is to split your training data into two sets: one to actually train the model and the other to validate your model using previously unseen data (in this validation set you will have access to the target values, for it was created from the training set, and so you'll be able to compute the errors). It is also common to split your training set into three new sets rather than two, as described here.
